# Authoring a usbtrace module

A module = `src/modules/<name>/` with three files. The build auto-discovers
`*.bpf.c` and `*.c`; no Makefile edits.

## Files

- `<name>.h` — shared kernel/user types. Include `"usbtrace/common.h"` and make
  `struct usbtrace_event_hdr hdr;` the FIRST member of your event struct. Use
  only fixed-width ints (BPF-safe).
- `<name>.bpf.c` — BPF program. Required prologue:
  ```c
  #include "vmlinux.h"
  #include <bpf/bpf_helpers.h>
  #include <bpf/bpf_core_read.h>
  #include <bpf/bpf_tracing.h>
  #include "<name>.h"
  char LICENSE[] SEC("license") = "GPL";
  ```
  Use a `BPF_MAP_TYPE_RINGBUF` named `events`. Read kernel fields ONLY via
  `BPF_CORE_READ()`. Put user-tunable filters in `const volatile struct ... cfg = {};`
  (the `= {}` initializer is required for clang ≤10 BTF emission).
- `<name>.c` — user space. Include `"<name>.skel.h"` + `"usbtrace/run.h"`,
  implement `parse_args`/`usage`/`run`, register via
  `USBTRACE_MODULE_REGISTER(<name>_module)`.

## Skeleton naming

`foo.bpf.c` → `foo.skel.h` with type `struct foo_bpf` and
`foo_bpf__open/load/attach/destroy`. Every skeleton also exposes the generic
`skel->skeleton` / `skel->maps.events`, which the run harness uses.

## run() contract — use the shared harness

Do NOT hand-roll load/attach/poll. The module owns only open + set cfg +
destroy; `usbtrace_run()` (`include/usbtrace/run.h`) does load → attach →
ring buffer → poll loop → teardown, so all modules behave identically:

```c
static int foo_run(volatile bool *running)
{
	struct foo_bpf *skel = foo_bpf__open();
	int rc;

	if (!skel) { ut_err("failed to open BPF skeleton"); return 1; }
	skel->rodata->cfg.filter_vid = (unsigned short)opts.vid;
	skel->rodata->cfg.filter_pid = (unsigned short)opts.pid;

	rc = usbtrace_run(&(struct usbtrace_run){
		.skeleton = skel->skeleton,
		.events   = skel->maps.events,
		.on_event = handle_event,
		.on_start = foo_on_start,   /* optional: print "tracing..." + header */
	}, running);

	foo_bpf__destroy(skel);
	return rc;
}
```

- `parse_args`: if your only options are `--vid/--pid/--help`, just
  `return usbtrace_filter_parse(argc, argv, &opts);`. Add extra options with
  `USBTRACE_FILTER_LONGOPTS` + `usbtrace_filter_getopt()` (see `urb`).
- `libbpf_set_print()` is done once in `main.c`; don't repeat it.
- Always `__builtin_memset` reserved ring records before filling.
- For a USB *class* driver, don't write a new event type — hook the driver's
  URB-completion callback and reuse the class-traffic foundation (`class.h`,
  `class_urb.bpf.h`, `class_stream.h`); see `.cursor/rules` / `docs/class.md`.

Mirror `src/modules/urb/` (core) or `src/modules/uvc/` (class) as canonical
examples.

## Hook portability

Prefer stable tracepoints when available; otherwise kprobes on USB core
functions (`usb_submit_urb`, `__usb_hcd_giveback_urb`, `usb_disconnect`, ...).
Guard for functions that may be absent on some kernels.
